sca.check.rationale: Setting net.ipv4.ip_forward and net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding to 0 ensures that a system with multiple interfaces (for example, a hard proxy), will never be able to forward packets, and therefore, never serve as a router.
sca.check.remediation: Set the following parameter in /etc/sysctl.conf or a file in /etc/sysctl.d/ ending in .conf: - net.ipv4.ip_forward = 0 Example: # printf '%s\n' "net.ipv4.ip_forward = 0" >> /etc/sysctl.d/60- netipv4_sysctl.conf Run the following script to set the active kernel parameters: #!/usr/bin/env bash { sysctl -w net.ipv4.ip_forward=0 sysctl -w net.ipv4.route.flush=1 } - IF - IPv6 is enabled on the system: Set the following parameter in /etc/sysctl.conf or a file in /etc/sysctl.d/ ending in .conf: - net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding = 0 Example: # printf '%s\n' "net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding = 0" >> /etc/sysctl.d/60- netipv6_sysctl.conf Run the following script to set the active kernel parameters: #!/usr/bin/env bash { sysctl -w net.ipv6.conf.all.forwarding=0 sysctl -w net.ipv6.route.flush=1 } Note: If these settings appear in a canonically later file, or later in the same file, these settings will be overwritten.
