Rule: 19007 (level 7) -> 'CIS Ubuntu Linux 24.04 LTS Benchmark v1.0.0.: Ensure audit_backlog_limit is sufficient.'
{"type":"check","id":1590222633,"policy":"CIS Ubuntu Linux 24.04 LTS Benchmark v1.0.0.","policy_id":"cis_ubuntu24-04","check":{"id":35726,"title":"Ensure audit_backlog_limit is sufficient.","description":"In the kernel-level audit subsystem, a socket buffer queue is used to hold audit events. Whenever a new audit event is received, it is logged and prepared to be added to this queue. The kernel boot parameter audit_backlog_limit=N, with N representing the amount of messages, will ensure that a queue cannot grow beyond a certain size. If an audit event is logged which would grow the queue beyond this limit, then a failure occurs and is handled according to the system configuration.","rationale":"If an audit event is logged which would grow the queue beyond the audit_backlog_limit, then a failure occurs, auditd records will be lost, and potential malicious activity could go undetected.","remediation":"Edit /etc/default/grub and add audit_backlog_limit=N to GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX. The recommended size for N is 8192 or larger. Example: GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX=\"audit_backlog_limit=8192\" Run the following command to update the grub2 configuration: # update-grub.","compliance":{"cis":"6.2.1.4","cis_csc_v8":"8.2","cis_csc_v7":"6.2,6.3","cmmc_v2.0":"AU.L2-3.3.1","hipaa":"164.312(b)","iso_27001-2013":"A.12.4.1","mitre_mitigations":"M1028","mitre_tactics":"TA0005","mitre_techniques":"T1562,T1562.001","nist_sp_800-53":"AU-7","pci_dss_v3.2.1":"10.2,10.3","pci_dss_v4.0":"10.2.1,10.2.1.1,10.2.1.2,10.2.1.3,10.2.1.4,10.2.1.5,10.2.1.6,10.2.1.7,10.2.2,5.3.4,6.4.1,6.4.2"},"rules":["f:/boot/grub/grub.cfg -> r:^\\s*\\t*linux && n:audit_backlog_limit=(\\p*\\d+) compare >= 8192"],"condition":"all","file":"/boot/grub/grub.cfg","result":"failed"}}
sca.type: check
sca.scan_id: 1590222633
sca.policy: CIS Ubuntu Linux 24.04 LTS Benchmark v1.0.0.
sca.check.id: 35726
sca.check.title: Ensure audit_backlog_limit is sufficient.
sca.check.description: In the kernel-level audit subsystem, a socket buffer queue is used to hold audit events. Whenever a new audit event is received, it is logged and prepared to be added to this queue. The kernel boot parameter audit_backlog_limit=N, with N representing the amount of messages, will ensure that a queue cannot grow beyond a certain size. If an audit event is logged which would grow the queue beyond this limit, then a failure occurs and is handled according to the system configuration.
sca.check.rationale: If an audit event is logged which would grow the queue beyond the audit_backlog_limit, then a failure occurs, auditd records will be lost, and potential malicious activity could go undetected.
sca.check.remediation: Edit /etc/default/grub and add audit_backlog_limit=N to GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX. The recommended size for N is 8192 or larger. Example: GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX="audit_backlog_limit=8192" Run the following command to update the grub2 configuration: # update-grub.
